<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-irrational-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Irrational Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
    
    <p>
      <term>Rational numbers:</term>
      These are numbers that can be written in the form <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are integers.These include whole numbers, fractions and terminating or recurring decimals. However,the 
      ancient Greeks famously discovered  that rational numbers alone cannot represent every point on the number line.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Irrational numbers account for points on the number line that cannot be represented by rational numbers ensuring that every point corresponds to a real number.
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>Irrational numbers:</term> These are numbers that cannot be written as a fraction <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, and when expressed as decimals,their decimal expansions are non-terminating and non-recurring. We will learn how 
      to identify these unique values, perform algebraic operations with radicals, 
      and understand why constants like <m>\pi</m> and <m>\sqrt{2}</m> are essential 
      for describing the world around us.
    </p>
 
  </introduction>

